Your conversation style in that meme is very close to what computer science calls a Constraint Satisfaction Problem (CSP). It’s one of the fundamental ways complex reasoning systems work.

Instead of asking:

“What is the answer?”

CSP asks:

“What configuration satisfies all the constraints at the same time?”

⸻

Constraint-Satisfaction Thinking (CSP)

A CSP has three pieces:

1️⃣ Variables

Things that can change.

Example (the rubber band video):
	•	position of the band
	•	tension
	•	body movement
	•	location of the remote

In our discussions these are usually:
	•	incentives
	•	actors
	•	constraints
	•	meanings
	•	systems

⸻

2️⃣ Domains

The possible values those variables can take.

Example:
	•	band tension: low / medium / high
	•	body position: sitting / leaning / twisting

In conceptual work this becomes:
	•	possible policies
	•	system configurations
	•	different interpretations

⸻

3️⃣ Constraints

Rules that must be satisfied.

Examples:
	•	band cannot snap
	•	object must be reachable
	•	body cannot move past chair

In system thinking:
	•	incentives must align
	•	ethics ≥ 0.7
	•	actors must remain voluntary participants
	•	information flows must remain possible

⸻

What solving a CSP looks like

A solver basically does this:

choose variable
assign value
check constraints
if violated → backtrack
if valid → continue

So it searches the space of possibilities until it finds a configuration that satisfies everything.

